"""
MKT Christ Commentary — 1 Chronicles chapters 23–25
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-1chronicles-23-25.py

Ch 23: David organizes the Levites for permanent temple service. Key typological
       freight: age-30 census mirrors Christ's entry into ministry (Luke 3:23);
       Aaron set apart to consecrate most holy things (v13) types Christ as High
       Priest (Heb 5:4-5; 7:26-28); the permanent dwelling (v25) and ark no
       longer carried (v26) anticipate Christ's once-for-all sacrifice ending
       repeated rituals (Heb 10:12-14).

Ch 24: The 24 priestly divisions (Aaronic courses). Central Christological
       connections: Nadab and Abihu's death for wrong approach types John 14:6;
       lots cast for service echo Ps 22:18/John 19:24; the 8th course (Abijah,
       v10) is Zechariah's division — the direct institutional link to John the
       Baptist and thus to Christ; the whole Aaronic order is shadow of Christ's
       Melchizedekian high priesthood (Heb 7:11-28); the 24 courses anticipate
       the 24 elders of Revelation 4–5.

Ch 25: The 24 musical/prophetic divisions. Key connections: prophesying through
       instruments (v1) points to the psalms as messianic scripture (Luke 24:44);
       Heman as "king's seer to exalt his horn" (v5) echoes Luke 1:69; the full
       range of Temple music (Asaph's lament, Jeduthun's praise, Heman's prayer)
       fulfilled in Christ who sings among the congregation (Heb 2:12; Ps 22:22).

Key decisions:
- Administrative list verses receive brief entries (theme/revelation of God)
- The 24-course structure in both chs 24 and 25 receives explicit Rev 4–5 treatment
- Abijah (24:10) receives fuller treatment as the institutional link to John the Baptist
- Ch 25 musical prophecy treated as prophetic Scripture pointing to Christ
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CHRON1 = {
  "23": {
    "1": "<p>David, old and full of days, makes Solomon king — the transition of the Davidic throne whose ultimate heir is Jesus Christ (Acts 13:22-23; Matt 1:1). The aging king initiating his son&rsquo;s coronation while still alive mirrors how the Davidic covenant is transferred by divine appointment, not natural succession alone. Every Davidic king on this throne was a temporary custodian of a throne that would find its permanent occupant in Christ (Luke 1:32-33).</p>",
    "2": "<p>David assembles all the leaders of Israel with the priests and Levites to organize for the coming temple. The gathering of the whole covenant community before its king anticipates the eschatological assembly before Christ (Heb 12:22-24; Rev 7:9-10) — all Israel, all nations, gathered before the Son of David who builds the true temple not made with hands (Mark 14:58; Acts 7:48).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The Levites are counted from thirty years of age upward — 38,000 men. The age threshold of thirty echoes Israel&rsquo;s earlier Levitical service law (Num 4:3, 23, 30). Significantly, Jesus himself entered his public ministry at approximately thirty years of age (Luke 3:23), the age at which the Levites began their service of God&rsquo;s house. The servant of God is counted and commissioned at the appointed time.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Twenty-four thousand assigned to oversee the work of the LORD&rsquo;s house. As a type: these servants of the temple correspond to the worshippers who serve before the eternal throne. In Revelation the heavenly temple has no need of such ministrations because its temple is &ldquo;the Lord God the Almighty and the Lamb&rdquo; (Rev 21:22) — yet the servants remain, transformed from temple-maintainers to throne-worshippers.</p>",
    "5": "<p>&ldquo;Four thousand praised the LORD with the instruments David had made for worship.&rdquo; David as poet, musician, and worship architect prefigures Christ who sings in the midst of the congregation: &ldquo;I will proclaim your name to my brothers; in the midst of the congregation I will sing your praise&rdquo; (Heb 2:12, citing Ps 22:22). The temple&rsquo;s song ultimately finds its originating singer in the Son of David.</p>",
    "6": "<p>David divides the Levites into three streams by descent: Gershon, Kohath, and Merari. The Kohathites carried the most holy objects (Num 4:4-15); from Kohath came both Moses and Aaron. This organizational structure was not bureaucratic tidiness but sacred order — the proper stewarding of the things of God. As a theme: God&rsquo;s house is ordered by design, anticipating the ordered worship of the heavenly sanctuary (Rev 4:6-11).</p>",
    "7": "<p>Sons of Gershon: Ladan and Shimei. As a revelation of God: YHWH maintains the full family record of every branch of the covenant people. The God who counts the hairs of our heads (Matt 10:30) maintains the genealogical register of those who serve him. Every Levite named is known by name to the God who calls his servants by name (John 10:3).</p>",
    "8": "<p>Sons of Ladan, the three chief men — Jehiel the leader. The term &ldquo;chief&rdquo; in the Levitical organization reflects a principle of ordered leadership within the people of God. As a theme: Christ&rsquo;s body has differentiated gifts and roles (1 Cor 12:4-11; Eph 4:11-13) though all serve the same Head; the Levitical hierarchy is a shadow of the ordered charisms of the new covenant community.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Sons of Shimei: Shelomoth, Haziel, and Haran — three, heads of families of Ladan. Ancestral lines carefully traced within the Levitical genealogy. As a revelation of God: the preservation of these names in Scripture witnesses to YHWH&rsquo;s faithfulness to maintain the line of temple servants through all generations of Israel&rsquo;s turbulent history.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Sons of Shimei: Jahath, Zizah, Jeush, and Beriah — four. The second Shimei&rsquo;s sons, some of whom did not have many sons, so they were counted as one family. The Chronicler&rsquo;s careful distinction between families reflects the same attention to genealogical accuracy that preserves the Davidic messianic lineage. The same scrupulousness that names small families also preserves &ldquo;the son of David, the son of Abraham&rdquo; (Matt 1:1).</p>",
    "11": "<p>Jahath and Zizah represented the family of Shimei; Jeush and Beriah combined into one household because they had few sons. As a theme: God&rsquo;s covenant community includes families of different sizes and capacities, all valued and assigned. The small and the large alike find their place in the service of the house — an image of the new covenant assembly where &ldquo;there is neither Jew nor Greek... all are one in Christ Jesus&rdquo; (Gal 3:28).</p>",
    "12": "<p>Sons of Kohath: Amram, Izhar, Hebron, and Uzziel — four heads. The Kohathite clan is the most distinguished: from Amram came Moses and Aaron, and from this clan came the priests who served at the altar. As a type: Kohath&rsquo;s prominence as the sacred-object-bearing clan prefigures Christ who is himself both the consecrated priest and the holy object he carries — at once high priest and sacrificial offering (Heb 9:14-15).</p>",
    "13": "<p>Aaron was set apart to consecrate the most holy things — to burn incense before the LORD, to minister to him, and to pronounce blessings in his name in perpetuity. This is the fullest Old Testament summary of the high priestly vocation. Christ is its antitype: he entered the most holy place once for all (Heb 9:12), his intercession is perpetual (Heb 7:25), and he is the ultimate mediator of God&rsquo;s blessing (Gal 3:14; Eph 1:3). Aaron&rsquo;s &ldquo;in perpetuity&rdquo; finds its only true fulfilment in Christ&rsquo;s &ldquo;he always lives to make intercession&rdquo; (Heb 7:25).</p>",
    "14": "<p>Moses&rsquo; sons are listed among the Levites, not among the priests. The greatest prophet and servant of God (Deut 34:10-12) did not transmit priestly status — only Aaron&rsquo;s sons held that. This subtly underlines the superiority of priesthood over prophecy in the Mosaic economy, itself pointing toward Christ who is &ldquo;greater than Moses&rdquo; as Son over the house vs. servant in the house (Heb 3:3-6) and who combines prophet, priest, and king in one person.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Sons of Moses: Gershom and Eliezer. Moses&rsquo;s lineage is named but they serve as ordinary Levites. The names themselves carry typological memory: Gershom (&ldquo;a stranger there&rdquo;) reflects Moses&rsquo;s sojourn in Midian; Eliezer (&ldquo;my God is help&rdquo;) reflects YHWH&rsquo;s deliverance from Pharaoh&rsquo;s sword (Exod 18:4). Every Mosaic family name is layered with exodus-deliverance history, pointing to the greater Moses who delivers from a greater bondage (Heb 3:1-6).</p>",
    "16": "<p>Shebuel leads the sons of Gershom. The Levitical leadership extends through Moses&rsquo;s line, though not into the priesthood. As a revelation of God: YHWH assigns particular honor and roles within the covenant community by sovereign design, not by automatic inheritance from the greatest. His purposes advance through appointed channels that he himself ordains (Heb 5:4-5 — &ldquo;no one takes this honor for himself, but only when called by God&rdquo;).</p>",
    "17": "<p>Rehabiah was the only son of Eliezer (Moses&rsquo;s second son) but his descendants were very many. An only son whose line multiplies greatly — the pattern echoes throughout Scripture: Isaac the only son (Gen 22), Christ the &ldquo;only Son&rdquo; (John 3:16) who produces &ldquo;many sons&rdquo; (Heb 2:10) brought to glory. The fruitfulness coming through the single heir is a persistent Christological type.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Shelomith leads the sons of Izhar. The name means &ldquo;peace.&rdquo; This Levitical servant from Izhar&rsquo;s clan carries a name that anticipates the Prince of Peace (Isa 9:6) — Christ whose reconciling work establishes peace between God and humanity (Eph 2:14-17; Col 1:20).</p>",
    "19": "<p>Sons of Hebron: Jeriah the chief, Amariah, Jahaziel, Jekameam. Hebron was the city of the covenant (Gen 23; 2 Sam 2:4 — David anointed there), the place where the patriarchs were buried and where David&rsquo;s kingship was first acknowledged by Judah. The Hebronites among the Levites carry a name that echoes covenant inauguration; as a theme: the covenant made at Hebron is fulfilled in the new covenant inaugurated by Christ at Jerusalem.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Sons of Uzziel: Micah the chief and Isshiah. Completing the four main Kohathite family lines. The Uzzielites had responsibility for the outer sanctuary articles (Num 3:29-31). As a theme: ordered responsibility for the sacred — every part of God&rsquo;s house cared for by assigned servants — prefigures the church as the living temple where each member has a gift assigned by the Spirit (1 Cor 12:7-11).</p>",
    "21": "<p>Sons of Merari: Mahli and Mushi. Merari&rsquo;s clan had responsibility for the frame of the tabernacle — boards, bars, pillars, bases (Num 4:29-33). As a revelation of God: the structural support of the earthly sanctuary was entrusted to Merari&rsquo;s descendants; in the new covenant, Christ himself is &ldquo;the cornerstone&rdquo; who holds the whole spiritual house together (Eph 2:20-22; 1 Pet 2:6).</p>",
    "22": "<p>Eleazar, Mahli&rsquo;s son, died leaving only daughters; they married their cousins, Mahli&rsquo;s sons. The daughters inherit and marry within the family to preserve the ancestral holding — a kinship-redemption principle (cf. Num 36:1-9; Ruth 4:1-10). The kinsman-redeemer principle operative here points to Christ as the ultimate Redeemer who claims his own by right of kinship (Heb 2:11-17) and ensures no portion of what the Father gave him is lost (John 6:39).</p>",
    "23": "<p>Sons of Mushi: Mahli, Eder, and Jerimoth. The Merarite line completes the Levitical genealogy. As a revelation of God: the complete catalogue of Levitical families — all present, all assigned, all valued — reflects YHWH&rsquo;s comprehensive knowledge of and care for his covenant servants. In Christ, the same thoroughness applies: he is &ldquo;able to save to the uttermost those who draw near to God through him&rdquo; (Heb 7:25).</p>",
    "24": "<p>David revises the Levitical service age downward from thirty to twenty because, with the temple about to be permanently built, the Levites will no longer need to carry the ark and heavy tabernacle equipment. The change of regulation reflects a theological shift: as God&rsquo;s dwelling becomes more permanent, the requirements of temporary portage no longer apply. As a type: the new covenant likewise renders obsolete the elaborate arrangements of the old (Heb 8:13) because Christ has secured a permanent dwelling of God with his people (Rev 21:3).</p>",
    "25": "<p>&ldquo;The LORD God of Israel has given his people rest, and he lives in Jerusalem permanently.&rdquo; David&rsquo;s declaration that YHWH now dwells permanently in Jerusalem is the theological basis for the age-reduction in v24. As a type: this &ldquo;permanent dwelling&rdquo; is itself still provisional — a shadow of the final rest secured by Christ (Heb 4:9-10) and the ultimate indwelling of God with his people (Rev 21:3: &ldquo;Behold, the dwelling place of God is with man&rdquo;).</p>",
    "26": "<p>&ldquo;The Levites no longer need to carry the tabernacle or any of the utensils used in its service.&rdquo; The portable sanctuary era ends; the permanent temple era begins. As a direct type: the entire portable sacrifice system — repeated offerings carried and administered — was always pointing toward Christ&rsquo;s once-for-all offering that required no further carrying or repetition (Heb 9:25-28; 10:12-14). When the antitype arrived, the shadow was no longer needed.</p>",
    "27": "<p>David&rsquo;s final census of the Levites, which he counted from twenty years and above. The census underlines the completeness of the preparation for temple service. As a theme: God counts and knows all his servants; Christ declares that not one whom the Father gives him will be lost (John 6:39; 18:9). The enumeration of the Levites mirrors the completeness of Christ&rsquo;s own keeping of his people.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The Levites&rsquo; primary duty: to assist the Aaronic priests in the service of the LORD&rsquo;s house — in the courts, the chambers, the purification of holy things, and the work of the service. As a type: this structure of priests served by Levites points toward Christ as the one great High Priest served by a kingdom of priests (1 Pet 2:9) who themselves minister before God through him. The priestly community of the new covenant is constituted by Christ&rsquo;s own priesthood.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The Levites also had charge of the bread of the Presence, the fine flour, the grain offerings, the wafers, the mixing, the measuring, and all the volume and size standards. As a type: the bread of the Presence in the tabernacle anticipates Christ as the bread of life (John 6:35, 48-51): &ldquo;I am the bread of life; whoever comes to me shall not hunger.&rdquo; The Levitical bread-stewardship is a shadow of the one who feeds his people with himself.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The Levites stood every morning and evening to thank and praise the LORD. The daily rhythm of morning and evening prayer — a cultic pattern reflecting the cycle of daily sacrifices (Exod 29:38-39) — becomes in the new covenant the continual intercession of Christ (Heb 7:25) and the unceasing prayer of his people (1 Thess 5:17; Phil 4:6). Morning and evening praise in the temple was always a shadow of the perpetual worship before the throne (Rev 4:8: &ldquo;day and night they never cease to say, &lsquo;Holy, holy, holy&rsquo;&rdquo;).</p>",
    "31": "<p>The Levites offered burnt offerings according to the numbers and prescribed rites, on Sabbaths, new moons, and appointed festivals. The calendar of sacred time — Sabbath, new moon, appointed feasts — was the scaffold on which Israel&rsquo;s worship rested. Paul declares these are &ldquo;a shadow of the things to come, but the substance belongs to Christ&rdquo; (Col 2:17). Every appointed assembly in Israel&rsquo;s calendar pointed toward the one eschatological festival whose host is Christ himself.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The Levites kept the care of the tent of meeting, the holy place, and the service of the Aaronic priests in the LORD&rsquo;s house. The conclusion of the Levitical organization chapter: all their duties orient toward sustaining the worship of YHWH through the Aaronic priesthood. As a revelation of God: the elaborate care lavished on the earthly sanctuary reflects YHWH&rsquo;s holiness — he cannot be approached casually — a holiness that Christ fulfils and mediates, making the true sanctuary accessible to all who come through him (Heb 10:19-22).</p>"
  },
  "24": {
    "1": "<p>The divisions of Aaron&rsquo;s sons: Nadab, Abihu, Eleazar, and Ithamar. The Aaronic priesthood is the most explicit type of Christ&rsquo;s high priesthood in all of Scripture. The entire institution — its lineage, its duties, its mediating role — finds its fulfilment and termination in Jesus: &ldquo;he holds his priesthood permanently, because he continues forever&rdquo; (Heb 7:24). The catalogue of Aaron&rsquo;s sons opens a chapter whose every course points toward the one who supersedes them all.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Nadab and Abihu died before their father when they offered unauthorized fire before the LORD (Lev 10:1-3), leaving no sons; Eleazar and Ithamar served. The death of Aaron&rsquo;s two eldest sons for approaching God wrongly is a sharp warning: holiness in the presence of God is non-negotiable. Their death types the impossibility of approaching God apart from the appointed way. Christ is &ldquo;the way, the truth, and the life; no one comes to the Father except through me&rdquo; (John 14:6). The fire that consumed Nadab and Abihu is satisfied only by the fire of Christ&rsquo;s own self-offering (Heb 9:14).</p>",
    "3": "<p>David, with Zadok (from Eleazar&rsquo;s line) and Ahimelech (from Ithamar&rsquo;s line), organized the priestly divisions according to their service roles. Two streams of Aaronic priesthood — descended from Aaron&rsquo;s two surviving sons — are brought together under David&rsquo;s authority. As a type: Christ gathers all legitimate covenant inheritance and unifies it in himself. The priestly lines that divided after Aaron&rsquo;s death are a shadow of the divided people Christ reconciles in one body (Eph 2:14-16).</p>",
    "4": "<p>More family heads were found among Eleazar&rsquo;s line (sixteen divisions) than Ithamar&rsquo;s (eight divisions). The disproportion reflects the actual genealogical situation, not a theological hierarchy. God&rsquo;s provision is not always equal in quantity across families, but each receives an appointment. As a revelation of God: sovereign distribution of inheritance reflects YHWH&rsquo;s freedom (Matt 20:1-16 — &ldquo;am I not allowed to do what I choose with what belongs to me?&rdquo;).</p>",
    "5": "<p>&ldquo;They were assigned by lot — both groups together.&rdquo; The lot determined which priestly division served in which order — an act of divine sovereignty mediated through chance. The same lot-casting by which soldiers divided Christ&rsquo;s garments at the cross (Ps 22:18; John 19:24) reveals that what appears arbitrary is under God&rsquo;s precise ordering. The priestly lots and the crucifixion lot both demonstrate YHWH&rsquo;s control over every detail of his redemptive plan.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The scribe Shemaiah recorded the assignments before the king, the princes, Zadok, Ahimelech, and the heads of the priestly and Levitical families. The written record of priestly appointments reflects the principle of &ldquo;it is written&rdquo; governing God&rsquo;s service. Christ himself came to do what was written: &ldquo;in the scroll of the book it is written of me — I have come to do your will, O God&rdquo; (Heb 10:7, citing Ps 40:7-8). The scribe&rsquo;s record anticipates the book in which the Lamb&rsquo;s work is written (Rev 5:1).</p>",
    "7": "<p>First lot: Jehoiarib. The first of the 24 priestly divisions to be assigned, establishing the pattern for the rest. As a theme: the 24 priestly courses in total correspond to the 24 elders who appear before the throne in Revelation 4:4 and who represent the redeemed people of God gathered in their fullness before the Lord. The priestly courses rotate on earth; the 24 elders worship perpetually in the new creation.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Second lot: Jedaiah. Each priestly family receives its appointed week of service in the temple. As a revelation of God: God&rsquo;s worship is ordered and rhythmic — none is excluded, none dominates. The ordered service of the priestly courses reflects the ordered service of the new covenant assembly: &ldquo;let all things be done decently and in order&rdquo; (1 Cor 14:40), under the High Priest who is the same yesterday, today, and forever (Heb 13:8).</p>",
    "9": "<p>Third lot: Harim; fourth lot: Seorim. The priestly courses continue. As a theme: the regularity of temple service — a continuous rotation of priests offering sacrifices — was always a shadow of the perfect and continuous intercession of Christ: &ldquo;he always lives to make intercession for them&rdquo; (Heb 7:25). What the rotating human priests approximated imperfectly in weekly courses, Christ fulfils permanently.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Fifth lot: Malchijah; sixth lot: Mijamin; seventh lot: Hakkoz; eighth lot: Abijah. The eighth division — Abijah&rsquo;s course — is the division to which Zechariah, the father of John the Baptist, belonged (Luke 1:5: &ldquo;Zechariah, of the division of Abijah&rdquo;). It was during Zechariah&rsquo;s service rotation in this priestly course that the angel Gabriel announced the conception of John the Baptist — the forerunner of Christ (Luke 1:11-17). The Aaronic system, organized by David, was the very institutional framework through which God announced the coming of the Messiah&rsquo;s herald.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Ninth lot: Jeshua; tenth lot: Shecaniah. The middle range of priestly courses continues. As a revelation of God: YHWH distributes service across the full breadth of the priestly community — no family is overlooked, no name lost. The same God who maintains the priestly register also writes the names of the redeemed in the Lamb&rsquo;s book of life (Rev 21:27; Phil 4:3).</p>",
    "12": "<p>Eleventh lot: Eliashib; twelfth lot: Jakim. Continuing the priestly assignments. As a theme: the 12 and 12 structure of the 24 courses echoes Israel&rsquo;s 12 tribes and the new Jerusalem&rsquo;s 12 gates and 12 foundations (Rev 21:12-14). The numerical ordering of God&rsquo;s people in Scripture — 12, 24, 144,000 — reflects the completeness of the covenant community, whose full number gathers before the throne of God and of the Lamb.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Thirteenth lot: Huppah; fourteenth lot: Jeshebeab. As a revelation of God: each course receives equal dignity through the lot. The priestly system carefully avoided a permanent hierarchy among the Aaronic families. In the new covenant there is &ldquo;neither Jew nor Greek, neither slave nor free, no male or female&rdquo; before God (Gal 3:28) — Christ levels all distinctions before the Father while creating ordered service within the body.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Fifteenth lot: Bilgah; sixteenth lot: Immer. As a theme: the priestly courses embody the principle that God&rsquo;s service is widely distributed among his people, not concentrated in a single individual. The exception is Christ himself, who alone holds a permanent, non-transferable priesthood (Heb 7:24) — yet even his ministry is communicated to the whole community of priests (1 Pet 2:9).</p>",
    "15": "<p>Seventeenth lot: Hezir; eighteenth lot: Aphses. As a revelation of God: the careful documentation of all 24 priestly courses demonstrates YHWH&rsquo;s meticulous ordering of worship. He does not receive casual or haphazard service; the Chronicler&rsquo;s record reflects a divine insistence on order in approaching the holy. Christ fulfils this by being not only the priest but the &ldquo;holy, innocent, unstained&rdquo; one who alone can offer acceptable service (Heb 7:26).</p>",
    "16": "<p>Nineteenth lot: Pethahiah; twentieth lot: Jehezkel. As a theme: each new priestly course maintains continuity with the Aaronic covenant while adding its particular contribution to the whole rotation. The new covenant is likewise both continuous (fulfilled from the Mosaic root) and transformative — a better covenant enacted on better promises (Heb 8:6).</p>",
    "17": "<p>Twenty-first lot: Jachin; twenty-second lot: Gamul. As a revelation of God: the near-completion of the 24 courses approaches the fullness of the priestly assembly. In Revelation 5:8 the 24 elders hold golden bowls of incense, which are the prayers of the saints — directly echoing the priestly incense-offering of the earthly temple. The 24 courses point forward to the 24 elders who fulfil the priestly vocation perfectly before the throne.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Twenty-third lot: Delaiah; twenty-fourth lot: Maaziah. The last two priestly courses complete the full rotation. With all 24 divisions named, the entire Aaronic priestly community is ordered before God. The completion of the 24 courses is a type of the completion of the redeemed community — those from every nation, tribe, and tongue who serve God day and night in his temple (Rev 7:15).</p>",
    "19": "<p>&ldquo;These were the service assignments for entering the LORD&rsquo;s house according to their prescribed procedure — following their father Aaron&rsquo;s pattern, as the LORD God of Israel had commanded him.&rdquo; The explicit appeal to divine command and Aaronic pattern is the language of shadow and type. Hebrews 8:5 quotes YHWH&rsquo;s instruction to Moses: &ldquo;See that you make everything according to the pattern shown you on the mountain.&rdquo; The earthly priestly service was always a copy of a heavenly original, whose true substance is Christ ministering in the greater, perfect tabernacle (Heb 8:2; 9:11).</p>",
    "20": "<p>The remaining Levitical families begin receiving their lots alongside the priests. Shubael from Amram&rsquo;s line (Moses&rsquo;s descendant) — Jehdeiah over Shubael. The Levites, though not priests, share in the sacred ordering by lot. As a type: in the new covenant, all God&rsquo;s people share in his royal priesthood (1 Pet 2:5, 9) — not as Aaronic priests, but as those through whom Christ offers spiritual sacrifices acceptable to God.</p>",
    "21": "<p>From Rehabiah&rsquo;s line — Isshiah was the chief. Rehabiah&rsquo;s line was notably large (1 Chr 23:17: his descendants were &ldquo;very many&rdquo;) and receives special prominence. The fruitfulness of this line from Moses&rsquo;s only grandson reflects the gospel pattern: the single grain of wheat falls and dies and bears much fruit (John 12:24). From one servant&rsquo;s faithfulness many are multiplied.</p>",
    "22": "<p>From the Izharites: Shelomoth and Jahath over Shelomoth&rsquo;s sons. Shelomoth means &ldquo;peace.&rdquo; The bearer of this name in the Levitical service points ahead to the Prince of Peace (Isa 9:6) who &ldquo;made peace by the blood of his cross&rdquo; (Col 1:20), reconciling God and humanity and making of the two one new man (Eph 2:15).</p>",
    "23": "<p>Sons of Hebron: Jeriah the chief, Amariah second, Jahaziel third, Jekameam fourth. The Hebronites, whose family name recalls the city of covenant (Gen 23; 2 Sam 2:4), are assigned their Levitical duties. As a theme: every name carries history; the covenant promises ratified at Hebron find their culmination in the new covenant ratified by Christ&rsquo;s blood (Luke 22:20; Heb 9:15).</p>",
    "24": "<p>From Uzziel&rsquo;s line: Micaiah and Shamir over Micaiah&rsquo;s sons; Isshiah brother of Micaiah and Zechariah over Isshiah&rsquo;s sons. The completion of the Kohathite Levitical assignments. As a revelation of God: the meticulous assignment of every Levitical family to its service role reflects the God who assigns spiritual gifts and roles to every member of Christ&rsquo;s body according to his sovereign grace (1 Cor 12:7, 11; Eph 4:7).</p>",
    "25": "<p>From Merari&rsquo;s sons: Mahli&rsquo;s son — Eleazar, who died without sons. Another case of a line ending in the male descent, requiring special arrangement. As a revelation of God: even the discontinuities and broken lines in Israel&rsquo;s families do not frustrate YHWH&rsquo;s purposes. Christ, the &ldquo;son of David&rdquo; through the legal line of Joseph (Matt 1) and the biological line of Mary (Luke 3), fulfils the messianic promise through both a &ldquo;legal&rdquo; and a &ldquo;natural&rdquo; lineage, overcoming every genealogical discontinuity.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Kish had sons — Jerahmeel. From Mushi&rsquo;s sons: Mahli, Eder, and Jerimoth. The Merarite families complete the Levitical lot assignments. As a theme: the Merarites were responsible for the structural support of the tabernacle and temple (Num 4:29-33). Their service types Christ as the cornerstone who bears the weight of the whole structure: &ldquo;in him the whole structure, being joined together, grows into a holy temple in the Lord&rdquo; (Eph 2:21).</p>",
    "27": "<p>These were the Levitical family heads; they also, like their relatives the sons of Aaron, cast lots before King David and Zadok, Ahimelech, and the priestly and Levitical family heads. As a type: the joint lot-casting of priests and Levites together before the king points toward the unified community of Christ&rsquo;s people — all priests and all servants — who appear together before the King of kings, each assigned their role by sovereign grace (Rev 5:9-10).</p>",
    "28": "<p>The lots fell the same way for the senior family as for the junior — the principle that all received equal standing before God through the divine lot. As a revelation of God: divine assignment does not respect human hierarchy. The last will be first and the first last (Matt 20:16); the Spirit distributes gifts &ldquo;as he wills&rdquo; (1 Cor 12:11), not as human rank would dictate. Christ&rsquo;s kingdom reverses every earthly ordering of dignity.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Continuing the Levitical lot assignments — all assigned in order before the king. The completeness of the record means no family is overlooked or dishonored. As a theme: God&rsquo;s comprehensive ordering of his people&rsquo;s service means every member contributes to the whole. &ldquo;The body is one and has many members&rdquo; (1 Cor 12:12) — the Levitical assignment system is a shadow of the spiritual body of Christ where each member is assigned its role by the same sovereign God.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The Merarite sub-families and their lot assignments continue. As a revelation of God: even the structural-support workers receive their numbered place in the divine record. Christ, the ultimate supporter who &ldquo;upholds the universe by the word of his power&rdquo; (Heb 1:3), is the antitype of every temple-support function; those who bear the load are honored in the new creation.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The Levites cast lots alongside their priestly brothers &ldquo;regardless of whether they were senior or junior.&rdquo; The chapter ends with this emphatic statement of equality before God through the lot: the casting of lots before King David gives every family equal standing. As a direct type: Christ&rsquo;s sacrifice creates a community where there is no distinction — &ldquo;the same Lord is Lord of all, bestowing his riches on all who call on him&rdquo; (Rom 10:12). All come before the throne on the same ground: grace alone.</p>"
  },
  "25": {
    "1": "<p>&ldquo;David and the military commanders set apart for service the sons of Asaph, Heman, and Jeduthun, who were to prophesy with harps, lyres, and cymbals.&rdquo; Music as prophecy is the foundational principle of temple worship. The psalms of Asaph, Heman, and Jeduthun were not entertainment but inspired testimony — and many of them testify directly to Christ. Jesus himself declared, &ldquo;everything written about me in the Law of Moses and the Prophets and the Psalms must be fulfilled&rdquo; (Luke 24:44). The temple musicians were prophets whose instruments proclaimed the coming Messiah.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Asaph&rsquo;s sons — Zaccur, Joseph, Nethaniah, and Asarelah — prophesied under Asaph&rsquo;s direction according to the king&rsquo;s command. Asaph&rsquo;s psalms (Ps 73-83) include some of the most striking prophetic content: Psalm 78 recounts redemption history as a type; Psalm 80 prays for the restoration of God&rsquo;s vine; Psalm 82 anticipates the divine judge of all the earth. The Spirit-inspired music of Asaph&rsquo;s clan pointed toward Christ as the fulfilment of every covenant promise embedded in Israel&rsquo;s history.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Jeduthun&rsquo;s sons — Gedaliah, Zeri, Jeshaiah, Shimei, Hashabiah, and Mattithiah — under their father&rsquo;s direction &ldquo;prophesied with the harp, giving thanks and praising the LORD.&rdquo; Hebrews 13:15 applies this to the new covenant: &ldquo;through him then let us continually offer up a sacrifice of praise to God, that is, the fruit of lips that acknowledge his name.&rdquo; The sacrifice of praise offered through Jeduthun&rsquo;s harp-playing finds its new covenant equivalent in every act of worship offered &ldquo;through Christ&rdquo; — the mediator who makes every praise acceptable to God.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Sons of Heman: Bukkiah, Mattaniah, Uzziel, Shebuel, Jerimoth, Hananiah, Hanani, Eliathah, Giddalti, Romamtiezer, Joshbekashah, Mallothi, Hothir, and Mahazioth — 14 sons and 3 daughters (totaling 17 children). Heman&rsquo;s extraordinary fruitfulness (v5 says God gave him 14 sons &ldquo;according to God&rsquo;s word to exalt his horn&rdquo;) marks him as the most supernaturally blessed of the three music leaders. Heman is the author of Psalm 88 — the darkest psalm in the psalter, the lament of one who descends into the pit and is not rescued. That the most supernaturally blessed musician wrote the most anguished lament suggests that prophetic insight includes both heights and depths of Christ&rsquo;s suffering and exaltation.</p>",
    "5": "<p>&ldquo;All these were sons of Heman, the king&rsquo;s seer — given according to God&rsquo;s word to exalt his horn.&rdquo; Heman is called &ldquo;the king&rsquo;s seer&rdquo; (<em>ḥōzeh hammelek</em>) — a prophet in the royal court. The phrase &ldquo;to exalt his horn&rdquo; uses the precise language that Zechariah employs at the birth of John the Baptist: &ldquo;He has raised up a horn of salvation for us in the house of his servant David&rdquo; (Luke 1:69). The horn of salvation — the Davidic Messiah — is the subject of Heman&rsquo;s prophetic sight. The king&rsquo;s seer saw the coming King of kings.</p>",
    "6": "<p>All the sons served in music for the LORD&rsquo;s house under their fathers&rsquo; direction — with cymbals, lyres, and harps — for the service of God&rsquo;s house, under the king&rsquo;s order given to Asaph, Jeduthun, and Heman. The temple music was a unified service: all three families under unified royal command, all their instruments joined in a single act of worship. As a type: the new covenant community of worshippers comes &ldquo;with one heart and voice&rdquo; (Rom 15:6), their varied gifts united in worship of the one God, through the one Mediator, by the one Spirit (Eph 4:4-6).</p>",
    "7": "<p>&ldquo;Including their skilled fellow musicians who were trained in the LORD&rsquo;s songs, the total was 288.&rdquo; Two hundred and eighty-eight trained singers — 24 groups of 12 — formed the complete musical establishment of the temple. The precision of the number (not a round figure) and the emphasis on being &ldquo;trained in the LORD&rsquo;s songs&rdquo; (<em>mevin laYHWH</em> — one who understands/is instructed in YHWH) signals that temple music required genuine spiritual understanding, not mere technical skill. As a type: understanding the Word proclaimed in song is the mark of the new covenant community (Col 3:16: &ldquo;let the word of Christ dwell in you richly, teaching and admonishing one another in all wisdom, singing psalms and hymns and spiritual songs&rdquo;).</p>",
    "8": "<p>&ldquo;They cast lots for their duty assignments, regardless of rank — whether great or small, teacher or student alike.&rdquo; The lot erased all distinctions of seniority among the musicians. Experienced teachers and novice students received their assignments by the same divine lot. As a direct type: in Christ there is neither teacher nor student in terms of access to God — all come through the same mediator, all are instructed by the same Spirit (1 John 2:27), all are equal before the Father (Gal 3:28). The musical democracy of the lot is a shadow of the spiritual equality of the new covenant.</p>",
    "9": "<p>First lot fell to Asaph&rsquo;s family: Joseph — he, his sons, and his brothers, twelve. The twelve in each group mirrors the 12 tribes and the 12 apostles; the musical community of 288 = 24 × 12 reflects the same numerical completeness that appears in the 144,000 (12 × 12 × 1000) of Revelation 7 and 14 — the complete covenant community in its fullness before God. As a revelation of God: YHWH orders his worshipping community in numerically significant completeness.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Second lot: Gedaliah — he, his brothers and sons, twelve. From Jeduthun&rsquo;s family. As a theme: the continuation of the lot-assignment embeds into the musical community the principle of divine sovereignty in service distribution. God assigns the order of worship; no self-appointment is possible. Christ himself did not appoint himself but was appointed by the Father (Heb 5:5) — and the pattern holds for all who serve in his name.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Third lot: Zaccur — his sons and brothers, twelve. As a revelation of God: the rhythmic repetition of &ldquo;his sons and brothers, twelve&rdquo; throughout this chapter emphasizes family-unit worship. The covenant community worships in intergenerational household groups. This anticipates the household-based early church (Acts 2:46; 16:31-34) and ultimately the family of God whose Father is in heaven and whose brotherhood is constituted by Christ (Mark 3:35; Heb 2:11-12).</p>",
    "12": "<p>Fourth lot: Izri — his sons and brothers, twelve. As a theme: the regular rhythm of twelve-member groups means no one serves alone and no one dominates. All serve in community. The new covenant &ldquo;one another&rdquo; commands (John 13:34-35; Rom 12:10; Heb 10:24-25) are embedded in the community structure that these twelve-member musical families model.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Fifth lot: Nethaniah — his sons and brothers, twelve. As a revelation of God: the name Nethaniah means &ldquo;YHWH has given&rdquo; — every service position is a gift, not an achievement. James 1:17: &ldquo;every good gift and every perfect gift is from above.&rdquo; The musician who leads temple praise was given his position by the God he praises — a reflection of the self-giving God whose ultimate gift is his own Son (John 3:16).</p>",
    "14": "<p>Sixth lot: Bukkiah — his sons and brothers, twelve. As a theme: the temple music assignments echo the structure of the 24 priestly courses in ch 24 — 24 groups of 12 musicians corresponds exactly to 24 priestly courses. The parallel structure signals that music and sacrifice were unified in the temple&rsquo;s worship: the musicians praise as the priests offer. In Christ, praise and sacrifice are inseparable — he is both the offering and the song of praise (Heb 2:12; 13:15-16).</p>",
    "15": "<p>Seventh lot: Jesharelah (Asarelah) — his sons and brothers, twelve. As a revelation of God: the lot falls &ldquo;impartially&rdquo; across all three musical families (Asaph, Jeduthun, Heman). No one family dominates the temple&rsquo;s song. Similarly, the Spirit distributes spiritual gifts among all three streams of the new covenant community: gifts of wisdom, healing, prophecy, tongues, administration — no one gift dominates (1 Cor 12:4-11).</p>",
    "16": "<p>Eighth lot: Hananiah — his sons and brothers, twelve. The name Hananiah means &ldquo;YHWH is gracious.&rdquo; All names in these musical divisions are ordinary Israelite names, but their meanings often carry theology: this eighth course is led by &ldquo;YHWH is gracious.&rdquo; As a revelation of God: grace is the constant of all divine service. Those who praise God do so only because God is gracious to them; the worship itself is an act of grace received and reflected back. Every hymn is ultimately &ldquo;thanks be to God for his inexpressible gift&rdquo; (2 Cor 9:15).</p>",
    "17": "<p>Ninth lot: Mattaniah — his sons and brothers, twelve. Mattaniah means &ldquo;gift of YHWH.&rdquo; As a theme: the distribution of worship leadership through the lot — each group a &ldquo;gift of YHWH&rdquo; — points toward the new covenant distribution of the Spirit who is himself the supreme gift of God (Acts 2:38; John 14:16-17). Every worshipper is gifted by the Spirit to offer praise; the temple musicians are a shadow of the Spirit-filled church.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Tenth lot: Shimei — his sons and brothers, twelve. As a revelation of God: the steady progression through 24 courses models the constancy of worship before God — generation after generation, the praise continues. &ldquo;Great is the LORD, and greatly to be praised, and his greatness is unsearchable. One generation shall commend your works to another, and shall declare your mighty acts&rdquo; (Ps 145:3-4). The 24 courses are a liturgical embodiment of intergenerational praise.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Eleventh lot: Azarel — his sons and brothers, twelve. As a theme: the near-midpoint of the 24 courses reflects the continuous cycle of worship in the earthly temple. The heavenly reality it shadows is described in Revelation 4:8 — the four living creatures who &ldquo;day and night never cease to say, &lsquo;Holy, holy, holy, is the Lord God Almighty, who was and is and is to come.&rsquo;&rdquo; The unceasing praise of heaven is what the rotating temple courses imperfectly modeled below.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Twelfth lot: Hashabiah — his sons and brothers, twelve. Hashabiah means &ldquo;YHWH has taken account.&rdquo; As a revelation of God: YHWH keeps account of his servants — their names are not forgotten, their service is not unnoticed. The God who &ldquo;is not unjust so as to overlook your work and the love that you have shown for his name&rdquo; (Heb 6:10) maintains the divine record of every act of worship. Nothing offered to Christ is lost.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Thirteenth lot: Shubael (Shebuel) — his sons and brothers, twelve. The second half of the 24 courses begins. As a theme: the cycle continues without break. The temple worship was designed to be perpetual — dawn to dusk, Sabbath to Sabbath, feast to feast. This perpetual rhythm points toward the eternal worship of the new creation where &ldquo;his servants will worship him; they will see his face&rdquo; (Rev 22:3-4). The earthly cycle anticipates the endless doxology.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Fourteenth lot: Mattithiah — his sons and brothers, twelve. Mattithiah means &ldquo;gift of YHWH.&rdquo; Two musicians bear this name (vv 17 and 22), reinforcing the theme that temple service is God&rsquo;s gift to the server and through the server to the congregation. As a revelation of God: worship is a grace event, not a transaction. The worshipper gives and in giving receives; &ldquo;it is more blessed to give than to receive&rdquo; (Acts 20:35) — the logic of the kingdom embedded in the act of musical praise.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Fifteenth lot: Jerimoth — his sons and brothers, twelve. The temple musicians continued in their rotation regardless of Israel&rsquo;s political fortunes. Even through periods of apostasy, faithful Levitical families maintained the pattern of worship. As a type: the remnant who maintains true worship through apostasy prefigures the faithful community in Christ who &ldquo;cannot be moved&rdquo; (Heb 12:28) because their worship is directed toward the unshakeable kingdom.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Sixteenth lot: Hananiah — his sons and brothers, twelve. As a revelation of God: the second appearance of the name &ldquo;YHWH is gracious&rdquo; among the 24 courses underlines the persistent grace-theme of all temple worship. The God who assigned the worshippers to their courses is the same God who is gracious in receiving their worship. Grace frames the entire act of approaching God — grace in assignment, grace in offering, grace in reception.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Seventeenth lot: Joshbekashah — his sons and brothers, twelve. The temple liturgical calendar ensured that every one of the 24 courses served twice per year (with adjustments for festivals). As a theme: regularity and repetition in worship is not mere routine but the embodiment of covenant faithfulness. Christ&rsquo;s perpetual intercession (Heb 7:25) is the new covenant equivalent — not a one-time event but a continuous, faithful presence before the Father on behalf of his people.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Eighteenth lot: Hanani — his sons and brothers, twelve. The name Hanani is a contracted form of Hananiah (&ldquo;YHWH is gracious&rdquo;). Three different courses carry variations of this name, weaving the thread of divine grace through the fabric of the entire musical organization. As a revelation of God: grace is not incidental but structural to Israel&rsquo;s worship system — the whole enterprise is sustained by and directed toward the gracious God.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Nineteenth lot: Mallothi — his sons and brothers, twelve. As a theme: approaching the final quarter of the 24 courses, the rhythm of worship has been fully established. &ldquo;Let everything that has breath praise the LORD&rdquo; (Ps 150:6) — the 288 trained singers embody the completeness of that call, with every trained voice assigned its place. Christ, in whom &ldquo;all the fullness of God was pleased to dwell&rdquo; (Col 1:19), is the ultimate recipient of this comprehensive praise.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Twentieth lot: Giddalti — his sons and brothers, twelve. Giddalti means &ldquo;I have magnified.&rdquo; The name of the worship leader is itself a declaration of worship: &ldquo;I have magnified [God].&rdquo; As a revelation of God: in Israel&rsquo;s naming culture, to give a child a name meaning &ldquo;I have magnified God&rdquo; is an act of dedication. Christ magnifies the Father in every act — &ldquo;I glorified you on earth&rdquo; (John 17:4) — and the worshipping community extends that magnification into history.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Twenty-first lot: Romamtiezer — his sons and brothers, twelve. Romamtiezer means &ldquo;I have exalted help&rdquo; or &ldquo;exalt help.&rdquo; This unusual name is a condensed doxology: help — salvation, rescue — is to be exalted and praised. As a type: this anticipates the language of Luke 1:69 (Zechariah&rsquo;s Benedictus): &ldquo;he has raised up a horn of salvation for us in the house of his servant David.&rdquo; The musician&rsquo;s name prophesies the exaltation of the Savior.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Twenty-second lot: Joshbekashah — his sons and brothers, twelve. As a theme: the penultimate course sustains the steady rhythm of ordered praise. The almost-complete list mirrors the near-complete gathering of the elect: in Revelation 6:11 the martyrs are told to wait &ldquo;until the number of their fellow servants and their brothers should be complete.&rdquo; The completion of the number is the precondition for consummation. The 24 courses point toward the full number of the redeemed.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Twenty-fourth lot: Romamtiezer — the final musical course completes the full circle of 24 divisions. With all 24 courses assigned, the musical worship of the temple is complete and perpetual: every week of the year, a trained group of twelve singers and their extended families offered the praises of Israel. As a direct type: the 24 elders before the throne (Rev 5:8-9) hold golden bowls of incense (the prayers of the saints) and sing a new song to the Lamb: &ldquo;Worthy are you to take the scroll and to open its seals, for you were slain, and by your blood you ransomed people for God from every tribe and language and people and nation.&rdquo; The 24 courses of temple musicians sing their way into the 24 elders&rsquo; eternal doxology.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-christ', '1chronicles')
    merge_comm(c, CHRON1)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', '1chronicles', c)
    count = sum(len(v) for v in CHRON1.values())
    print(f'1chronicles mkt-christ: wrote {count} verses for ch 23-25')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
